  <refsect1>
    <title>DESCRIPTION</title>

    <para>This manual page documents briefly the
      <command>&dhpackage;</command> command.</para>

    <para>This manual page was written for the &debian; distribution
      because the original program does not have a manual page.
    </para>

    <para><command>&dhpackage;</command> is a free turn based 
      strategy game. It features a 2-dim. map that is tiled into 
      hexagons where units are placed. The object of the game 
      varies from map to map. The most commonly know goal is to
      completely eliminate an oppononet by detroying all his 
      units. Currently only email games against human opponents
      is fully implemented. 
    </para>

  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>OPTIONS</title>

    <para>These programs don not follow the usual GNU command line syntax,
      with long options starting with two dashes (`-').  A summary of
      options is included below.
    </para>

    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-cf, </option>
<option>--configfile </option><replaceable>file</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>uses the specified file as a configuration file for the program
</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-eg, </option>
<option>--emailgame </option><replaceable>file</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>opens the specified file in order to continue an email game</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-fs, </option>
<option>--fullscreen </option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>enable fullscreen mode (for overriding the setting in the
config file)</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-h</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Show summary of options.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-lm, </option>
<option>--loadmap </option><replaceable>file</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>starts the game with the given map</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-ns, </option>
<option>--nosound </option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>disable sound</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-sg, </option>
<option>--savegame </option><replaceable>file</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>opens the specified file in order to continue a game</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-v, </option>
<option>--verbose </option><replaceable>n</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>displays what the programm is currently doing. This is a very 
useful option when tracing problems. the higher n is set the more information
is displayed</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-w, </option>
<option>--window </option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>disable full screen mode so the program is run in a window
</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-x:</option><replaceable>n</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>sets the horizontal resolution to n; defaults to 800
</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-y:</option><replaceable>n</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>sets the horizontal resolution to n; defaults to 600
</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsect1>
